    "abstractNote": "The article analyzes the<i>K\u1e6f\u0101\u1e07\u0101 \u1e0f-Hudd\u0101y\u0113</i>, a legal work of the Syriac polymath and ecclesiastic leader Barhebraeus. The intertextual strategies are assessed, such as compilation, redaction and adaption of the <i>Hudd\u0101y\u0113</i>\u2019s source material, i.e. legal compendia by al-Ghaz\u0101l\u012b, by the \u1e24anaf\u012b al-Qud\u016br\u012b and texts from Christian tradition. It is argued that the different normative boundaries established by these source texts and then intertextually reworked by Barhebraeus in the <i>Hudd\u0101y\u0113 </i>can be read as (re-)negotiation of communal identity for a Christian community in an Islamic environment. Two treatments of unborn life and pregnancy are taken as an example: the funeral prayer for the miscarried child and financial compensation in case of induced miscarriage.",
